Begin, 1, %functions\n%c0, o.;e.;,

Nodes:



// Display Name, Type, Code, IO, reference-link

// Type
// 0 = execution node (the first input and output are execution nodes)
// 1 = basic node
// 2 = micro node (same as basic node, but smaller)
// 3 = An input node, it means there's an input tag somewhere on the node 
// 4 = macro node (same as micro node, but only shows the symbol)
// 5 = programmable node (same as basic node, except it interprets the code as Node Language to determine the output)

// Code
// The format for the node's inputs.
// %0 is replaced with the first input, %1 with the second, and so on. the order is based on the order in the IO.
// for example a python print node would look like "print(%0)",


// IO
// letterCode.InputName;
// letterCode will determine the colour of the node, defined under Types
// o.; separates the inputs from the outputs, so a complete node would look like
// b.Condition;o.;b.Result;

// You can prefix with another letter and dot to add a modifier, such as n.b.Condition
// - n
//  The nub will not be visible, but will contribute to the gradient
// - p
//  The nub is optional, this one needs a default value, so it's structured like p.defaultvalue.type.name, such as p.3.f.Number;
// - c
//  Custom nub. The name will be the only thing put in the nub's spot.
// - i
//  Instead of a nub, use the input tag for that type. i.b.; for example will create a checkbox, since I defined that as the input for bools.

// reference-link will be appended to the end of the documentation link to take users to the appropriate page for each function.
//Colour, 3, "%", c.s.<input type='color'>;o.;s.;,

Make Statement, 0, %0, e.;g.;o.;e.;, 
Custom, 3, %, i.s.;o.;g.;,
Set By Reference, 0, %0 = %1, e.;g.Ref;g.Value;o.;e.;,

// Node Language is a lot easier to use in header file modules
